1
00:00:33,960 --> 00:00:38,145
WOMAN: She came along the alley and up
the back stairs the way she always used to.

2
00:00:39,240 --> 00:00:41,860
Doc hadn't seen her in over a year.

3
00:00:41,960 --> 00:00:44,020
Nobody had.

4
00:00:44,120 --> 00:00:46,700
Back then it was always sandals...

5
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:49,260
bottom half of a flower-print bikini...

6
00:00:49,360 --> 00:00:53,020
and a faded
Country Joe and the Fish T-shirt.

7
00:00:53,120 --> 00:00:56,020
Tonight, she was all in flatland gear...

8
00:00:56,120 --> 00:00:58,860
hair a lot shorter than he remembered...

9
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:02,462
looking just like she swore
she would never look.

10
00:01:09,640 --> 00:01:11,310
Psst.

11
00:01:16,960 --> 00:01:18,949
That you, Shasta?

12
00:01:19,840 --> 00:01:21,783
[CHUCKLES]

13
00:01:23,280 --> 00:01:25,951
Thinks he's hallucinating.

14
00:01:26,520 --> 00:01:31,467
No, just a new package, I guess.

15
00:01:35,640 --> 00:01:37,424
[CHUCKLES]

16
00:01:41,120 --> 00:01:43,109
I need your help, Doc.

17
00:01:43,240 --> 00:01:45,263
[CHUCKLES]

18
00:01:45,520 --> 00:01:50,020
You know I have an office now?
It's like a day job and everything.

19
00:01:50,120 --> 00:01:54,420
I looked in the phone book
and almost went over there.

20
00:01:54,520 --> 00:01:59,228
Then I thought better for everyone
if this looks like a secret rendezvous.

21
00:01:59,920 --> 00:02:02,591
Is somebody keeping a close eye?

22
00:02:03,800 --> 00:02:07,382
Just spent an hour on surface streets
trying to make it look good.

23
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:08,781
[SIGHS]

24
00:02:13,880 --> 00:02:15,020
Uh...

25
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:16,460
[EXHALES]

26
00:02:16,560 --> 00:02:18,071
You want a beer?

27
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:21,820
How about a beer? You want a beer?

28
00:02:21,920 --> 00:02:23,226
Yeah.

29
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:29,110
DOC: Uh...

30
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:39,862
There's this guy.

31
00:02:40,520 --> 00:02:43,908
Gentleman of the straight-world
persuasion?

32
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:50,870
Okay, Doc.

33
00:02:53,480 --> 00:02:55,548
He's married.

34
00:02:57,560 --> 00:03:00,948
Some, uh... money situation?

35
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:05,140
And the wife, uh... she knows about you?

36
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:07,580
She's seeing somebody too.

37
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:09,740
But it's not just the usual.

38
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:12,740
I think they're working
on some creepy, little scheme.

39
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:15,100
To make off with the hubby's fortune?

40
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:19,271
Yeah, I think I've heard
of that happening once or twice.

41
00:03:20,080 --> 00:03:22,706
And you want me to do, uh...
what exactly?

42
00:03:26,400 --> 00:03:28,548
Is they want me in on it.

43
00:03:30,120 --> 00:03:33,100
They think I'm the one who can reach him
when he's vulnerable.

44
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:35,382
Or as much as he ever gets.

45
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:38,980
Bare-ass and asleep.

46
00:03:39,080 --> 00:03:41,182
I knew you'd understand.

47
00:03:43,720 --> 00:03:46,630
Are you still trying to figure out
if it's right or wrong?

48
00:03:53,720 --> 00:03:55,584
Worse than that.

49
00:03:58,440 --> 00:04:00,508
How much loyalty I owe him.

50
00:04:01,960 --> 00:04:03,630
Groovy.

51
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:05,900
All right...

52
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,980
emotions aside, let's look at the rent.

53
00:04:09,080 --> 00:04:11,340
How much of, uh... your rent's
he been picking up?

54
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:14,940
- All of it.
- Pretty, uh... hefty?

55
00:04:15,040 --> 00:04:16,580
For Hancock Park?

56
00:04:16,680 --> 00:04:19,460
You're giving him IOUs
for everything, of course.

57
00:04:19,560 --> 00:04:22,740
You fucker. If I had known
you were still this bitter...

58
00:04:22,840 --> 00:04:25,944
Me? I'm trying to be
professional, is all.

59
00:04:27,960 --> 00:04:29,340
All right.

60
00:04:29,440 --> 00:04:34,421
How much have the, uh... wifey
and boyfriend offered to cut you in for?

61
00:04:37,160 --> 00:04:38,780
It isn't what you're thinking.

62
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:41,187
Don't worry. Thinking comes later.

63
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:44,540
What else?

64
00:04:48,360 --> 00:04:50,144
I'm not sure.

65
00:04:50,840 --> 00:04:54,149
It sounds like they wanna commit him
to a loony bin.

66
00:04:57,080 --> 00:04:59,308
SORTILÈGE:
Back when they were together...

67
00:04:59,440 --> 00:05:04,260
she could go weeks without anything
more complicated than a pout.

68
00:05:04,360 --> 00:05:07,820
Now she was laying some heavy
combination of face ingredients...

69
00:05:07,920 --> 00:05:10,910
on Doc that he couldn't read at all.

70
00:05:11,840 --> 00:05:13,460
Argh. Fuck.

71
00:05:13,560 --> 00:05:19,100
SORTILÈGE: Come to think of it, there'd
never been this much sorrow in her voice.

72
00:05:19,200 --> 00:05:21,500
Heard you're seeing someone downtown?

73
00:05:21,600 --> 00:05:22,986
Penny?

74
00:05:24,080 --> 00:05:25,591
Some kind of junior DA?

75
00:05:26,880 --> 00:05:31,030
Yeah, you think, uh... somebody down there
could stop this before it happens?

76
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:33,827
Not too many places
I could go with this, Doc.

77
00:05:38,120 --> 00:05:39,631
[EXHALES]

78
00:05:41,080 --> 00:05:42,940
I'll talk to Penny.

79
00:05:43,040 --> 00:05:45,029
See what we can see.

80
00:05:46,080 --> 00:05:48,865
Your happy couple, they have names?

81
00:05:51,880 --> 00:05:53,869
It's Mickey Wolfmann.

82
00:05:56,280 --> 00:05:59,980
Who's always in the paper?
The real-estate big shot?

83
00:06:00,080 --> 00:06:01,420
Yeah.

84
00:06:05,960 --> 00:06:08,427
Can't tell anyone about this, Doc.

85
00:06:10,320 --> 00:06:11,820
Oh.

86
00:06:11,920 --> 00:06:13,180
Huh.

87
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:15,542
Deaf and dumb, part of my job.

88
00:06:17,480 --> 00:06:19,184
How do I reach you?

89
00:06:21,640 --> 00:06:23,310
You don't.

90
00:06:23,960 --> 00:06:27,380
I moved out of my old place.
Staying where I can anymore.

91
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:29,150
Don't ask.

92
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:32,790
There's room here.

93
00:06:35,560 --> 00:06:37,583
Walk me down to my car?

94
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:43,703
Someone might be watching.

95
00:06:51,320 --> 00:06:54,580
- You never did let me down, Doc.
- Don't worry. I'll...

96
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:57,067
No, I mean, really. Ever.

97
00:06:57,840 --> 00:06:59,100
Sure I did.

98
00:06:59,200 --> 00:07:01,951
No. You were always true.

99
00:07:07,360 --> 00:07:09,540
You know, you don't have to go.

100
00:07:09,640 --> 00:07:11,390
Watch your toes.

101
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:14,944
Vroom.

102
00:07:52,120 --> 00:07:55,740
SORTILÈGE: Doc ran through all the things
he hadn't asked Shasta.

103
00:07:55,840 --> 00:07:57,780
Like how much she'd come to depend on...

104
00:07:57,880 --> 00:08:01,580
Wolfmann's guaranteed level
of ease and power.

105
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:03,980
And least askable of all:

106
00:08:04,080 --> 00:08:07,662
How passionately did she really feel
about old Mickey?

107
00:08:11,360 --> 00:08:13,060
- Hey, what's up, Doc?
- Hey, Denis.

108
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:16,420
What's up, man?
What's going on? Doing all right?

109
00:08:16,520 --> 00:08:18,980
SORTILÈGE: Doc knew the likely reply:

110
00:08:19,080 --> 00:08:21,700
"I love him. What else?"

111
00:08:21,800 --> 00:08:23,780
With the unspoken footnote...

112
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:27,820
that the word these days
was being way too overused.

113
00:08:27,920 --> 00:08:29,545
DENIS: What you looking at?

114
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:36,500
DOC: You hungry?

115
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:38,780
DENIS:
Like Godzilla says to Mothra, man:

116
00:08:38,880 --> 00:08:40,500
"Let's go eat someplace."

117
00:08:40,600 --> 00:08:43,460
SORTILÈGE: So when Doc
and Denis came in that night...

118
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:46,869
it wasn't just the usual
hungry doper thing.

119
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:48,500
It was something else.

120
00:08:48,600 --> 00:08:52,580
And with Neptune moving
at last out of the Scorpio death-trip...

121
00:08:52,680 --> 00:08:56,500
and rising into the Sagittarian light
of the higher mind...

122
00:08:56,600 --> 00:08:59,540
it was bound to be
something love-related.

123
00:08:59,640 --> 00:09:02,140
And I thought I knew what it was.

124
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:03,751
So...?

125
00:09:05,560 --> 00:09:08,300
She stuck her head in for a minute.

126
00:09:08,400 --> 00:09:10,500
You feeling broken up?

127
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:13,620
Kind of weird
seeing her again, you know?

128
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:16,540
Yeah, I figured next time I saw her,
it'd be on the tube.

129
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:18,583
Not in person.

130
00:09:20,040 --> 00:09:22,860
- Well, you'd better do something about this.
- Heh.

131
00:09:22,960 --> 00:09:24,060
Yeah, again?

132
00:09:24,160 --> 00:09:26,580
Can't tell you enough:
Change your hair, change your life.

133
00:09:26,680 --> 00:09:28,140
Mm.

134
00:09:28,240 --> 00:09:31,140
Mm. Well, what do you recommend?

135
00:09:31,240 --> 00:09:32,900
It's up to you.

136
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:35,421
Follow your intuition.

137
00:09:37,480 --> 00:09:40,424
[BOTH SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

138
00:09:48,040 --> 00:09:49,340
[PHONE RINGS]

139
00:09:49,440 --> 00:09:50,540
Hello?

140
00:09:50,640 --> 00:09:52,230
DOC [OVER PHONE]: Hey, Aunt Reet?

141
00:09:53,640 --> 00:09:56,260
- Hello?
- Yes, honey. Make it quick.

142
00:09:56,360 --> 00:09:59,820
I got a live one tonight,
and I totally fucked up my face.

143
00:09:59,920 --> 00:10:03,940
DOC: Aw. Oh, okay. Mickey Wolfmann,
what can you tell me?

144
00:10:04,040 --> 00:10:06,580
Powerhouse in L.A. real estate.

145
00:10:06,680 --> 00:10:09,100
From the desert to the sea.

146
00:10:09,200 --> 00:10:12,740
Technically Jewish,
but wants to be a Nazi.

147
00:10:12,840 --> 00:10:14,300
What's he to you?

148
00:10:14,400 --> 00:10:15,780
DOC: Possible case.

149
00:10:15,880 --> 00:10:19,189
Let's say I wanted to hang out
and rap with this Wolfmann.

150
00:10:19,960 --> 00:10:22,100
Say it's a really bad idea.

151
00:10:22,200 --> 00:10:26,580
He goes around with a dozen bikers,
mostly Aryan Brotherhood alumni.

152
00:10:26,680 --> 00:10:28,220
Whoa, whoa, whoa. Wait.

153
00:10:28,320 --> 00:10:30,020
I flunked Social Studies...

154
00:10:30,120 --> 00:10:32,460
but, uh... Jews and Aryan Brotherhood...

155
00:10:32,560 --> 00:10:34,380
isn't there something about hatred?

156
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:38,020
No. Mickey's eccentric.
More and more lately.

157
00:10:38,120 --> 00:10:42,860
I'd say, stoned out of his fucking mind
since he discovered drugs.

158
00:10:42,960 --> 00:10:45,180
No offense to you, Doc.

159
00:10:45,280 --> 00:10:46,340
[MUTTERS]

160
00:10:46,440 --> 00:10:50,180
So where would I, uh... find him?
Like accidentally?

161
00:10:50,280 --> 00:10:54,260
Try the Channel View Estates,
his latest insult to the environment.

162
00:10:54,360 --> 00:10:57,540
The one that Bigfoot Bjornsen
does the commercials for?

163
00:10:57,640 --> 00:10:59,540
- REET: That's the one.
- Uh-huh.

164
00:10:59,640 --> 00:11:04,140
Maybe your old cop buddy's the one
who should be taking care of your case.

165
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:07,780
Yeah, well, I did think
about going to Bigfoot with this...

166
00:11:07,880 --> 00:11:11,860
but just as I reached for the phone,
history and all, I thought:

167
00:11:11,960 --> 00:11:13,300
Mm...

168
00:11:13,400 --> 00:11:16,980
- Well, maybe you're better off with the Nazis.
- DOC: Heh.

169
00:11:17,080 --> 00:11:18,180
All right, all right.

170
00:11:18,280 --> 00:11:22,340
REET: I got major liquid-liner issues.
I gotta get off now, Larry.

171
00:11:22,440 --> 00:11:23,701
All right.

172
00:11:24,560 --> 00:11:26,180
MAN 1 [ON TV]: Morning, Sam.

173
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:27,980
MAN 2 [ON TV]: Hey, man.

174
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:29,900
I don't want you paying rent.

175
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,940
Rent's a hassle.
I wanna see you in your own pad...

176
00:11:33,040 --> 00:11:34,340
Howdy, Bigfoot.

177
00:11:34,440 --> 00:11:36,140
MAN 2: ...at Channel View Estates...

178
00:11:36,240 --> 00:11:39,740
Artesia's newest and grooviest
residential housing development.

179
00:11:39,840 --> 00:11:41,860
No buzzkill credit checks.

180
00:11:41,960 --> 00:11:45,340
No rip-off minimum down payments.
That's not your bag.

181
00:11:45,440 --> 00:11:46,980
But check this out:

182
00:11:47,080 --> 00:11:51,460
Fully-equipped kitchen with automatic
self-cleaning oven and breakfast nook.

183
00:11:51,560 --> 00:11:52,980
Out of sight.

184
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:56,460
Attached one-car
and available two-car garage.

185
00:11:56,560 --> 00:11:58,020
And best of all...

186
00:11:58,120 --> 00:12:00,620
a view of the Dominguez
Flood Control Channel...

187
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:03,460
that can only be described in two words:

188
00:12:03,560 --> 00:12:05,150
Right on.

189
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:08,180
So, what's all this now?

190
00:12:12,240 --> 00:12:14,183
What's up, Doc?

191
00:12:14,640 --> 00:12:16,230
What...?

192
00:12:18,760 --> 00:12:22,540
"Michael Wolfmann, one of Los Angeles's
most prominent real estate developers...

193
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:24,700
announced at a press conference...

194
00:12:24,800 --> 00:12:28,100
he's proceeding with construction
of several housing developments...

195
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:30,580
the most immediate
to be Channel View Estates.

196
00:12:30,680 --> 00:12:32,260
- MAN: Hey, Doc.
- Howdy.

197
00:12:32,360 --> 00:12:34,900
Cop came around last night
looking for you again.

198
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:37,420
- Bigfoot?
- Yeah. That's the one.

199
00:12:37,520 --> 00:12:38,900
Huh.

200
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,740
I wonder why he didn't kick in my door
like usual.

201
00:12:41,840 --> 00:12:46,140
He might've been thinking about it, but said
something like, "Tomorrow's another day."

202
00:12:46,240 --> 00:12:48,069
Which would be today, right?

203
00:12:49,520 --> 00:12:52,021
Not if I can help it.

204
00:12:52,520 --> 00:12:56,020
All right, "Wolfmann,
known for his outlandish advertising...

205
00:12:56,120 --> 00:12:59,140
and aggressive style, has been...

206
00:12:59,240 --> 00:13:02,060
involved in the Southern
California real estate market..."

207
00:13:02,160 --> 00:13:05,150
for the past 23 fucking years, you know.

208
00:13:08,360 --> 00:13:10,420
- Morning, Doc.
- Hey. Morning, Petunia.

209
00:13:10,520 --> 00:13:13,460
- I love your Afro. Uh-huh.
- Oh, yeah? Thank you.

210
00:13:13,560 --> 00:13:16,470
Oh, Doc. You have someone
waiting in your office.

211
00:13:19,360 --> 00:13:20,985
- Doctor.
- Doctor.

212
00:13:24,880 --> 00:13:27,745
Hey, man. Sorry to, uh...
keep you waiting.

213
00:13:29,400 --> 00:13:32,620
- Dr. Sportello?
- That's right. What it is, my brother.

214
00:13:32,720 --> 00:13:35,780
Peace. I'm Tariq Khalil.

215
00:13:35,880 --> 00:13:37,020
Cool.

216
00:13:37,120 --> 00:13:38,631
Sit down.

217
00:13:39,640 --> 00:13:41,344
[DOC GRUNTS]

218
00:13:43,400 --> 00:13:45,580
What's up, man?
How can I help you today?

219
00:13:45,680 --> 00:13:50,420
There's this white boy I was
in the joint with. Aryan Brotherhood.

220
00:13:50,520 --> 00:13:54,620
We did some business, and, uh...
now we're both out and he still owes me.

221
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:58,180
I can't tell you the details,
but it's a whole lot of money.

222
00:13:58,280 --> 00:14:00,500
Mm. How about his name?

223
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:02,500
Glen Charlock.

224
00:14:02,600 --> 00:14:07,500
Mm-hm. And, um... you know
where he's staying now?

225
00:14:07,600 --> 00:14:09,420
I know where he works.

226
00:14:09,520 --> 00:14:12,385
He's a bodyguard
for this builder named Wolfmann.

227
00:14:15,400 --> 00:14:18,071
[HUMMING]

228
00:14:20,600 --> 00:14:24,060
If you don't mind my asking, Mr. Khalil,
how'd you hear about me?

229
00:14:24,160 --> 00:14:27,100
Sledge. Sledge Poteet.

230
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:28,340
Wow.

231
00:14:28,440 --> 00:14:30,100
Blast from the past. Far out.

232
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:31,660
Yeah.

233
00:14:31,760 --> 00:14:35,300
He said you helped him out
of a situation back in '67.

234
00:14:35,400 --> 00:14:37,420
First time I got shot at.

235
00:14:37,520 --> 00:14:39,620
If you don't mind an obvious question...

236
00:14:39,720 --> 00:14:42,660
you, uh... know where
this Glen Charlock works.

237
00:14:42,760 --> 00:14:45,340
Why not, uh... just go over there
and look him up directly?

238
00:14:45,440 --> 00:14:49,380
Well, because Wolfmann likes to surround
himself with the Aryan Brotherhood.

239
00:14:49,480 --> 00:14:51,140
Day and night.

240
00:14:51,240 --> 00:14:56,260
And, see, outside of Glen,
I ain't never liked the company of Nazis.

241
00:14:56,360 --> 00:15:01,020
Mm-hm. So, uh... send some white guy
to get his head hammered?

242
00:15:01,120 --> 00:15:04,260
- More or less.
- Mm.

243
00:15:04,360 --> 00:15:07,420
Now when you were inside,
were you in a gang?

244
00:15:07,520 --> 00:15:09,748
The Black Guerrilla Family.

245
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:15,700
And you say you did business with who now?
The Aryan Brotherhood?

246
00:15:15,800 --> 00:15:17,180
Listen...

247
00:15:17,280 --> 00:15:21,220
we found we share some of the similar
opinions about the U.S. government.

248
00:15:21,320 --> 00:15:22,660
That's all.

249
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:24,669
I can dig.

250
00:15:26,720 --> 00:15:28,860
There's something else?

251
00:15:28,960 --> 00:15:31,301
Matter of fact, there is.

252
00:15:32,200 --> 00:15:35,660
My old street gang. The Artesia Crips.

